04697nam a22007575i 9780801466069DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979575812  a97808014660697 a10.7591/97808014660692doi  a(DE-B1597)478498  a(OCoLC)808344444  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJC571b.W876 2016 7aPOL0410002bisacsh04a3232231 aWong, Wendy H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInternal Affairs :bHow the Structure of NGOs Transforms Human Rights /cWendy H. Wong. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2012] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Internal Affairs and External Influence -- t1. Salience in Human Rights -- t2. The Importance of Organizational Structure -- t3. Amnesty International: The NGO That Made Human Rights Important -- t4. Other Models of Advocating Change -- t5. Using Campaigns to Examine Organizational and Ideational Salience -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy are some international nongovernmental organizations (NGOs) more politically salient than others, and why are some NGOs better able to influence the norms of human rights? Internal Affairs shows how the organizational structures of human rights NGOs and their campaigns determine their influence on policy. Drawing on data from seven major international organizations—the International Committee of the Red Cross, Amnesty International, Human Rights Watch, Médecins sans Frontières, Oxfam International, Anti-Slavery International, and the International League of Human Rights—Wendy H. Wong demonstrates that NGOs that choose to centralize agenda-setting and decentralize the implementation of that agenda are more successful in gaining traction in international politics.Challenging the conventional wisdom that the most successful NGOs are those that find the "right" cause or have the most resources, Wong shows that how NGOs make and implement decisions is critical to their effectiveness in influencing international norms about human rights. Building on the insights of network theory and organizational sociology, Wong traces how power works within NGOs and affects their external authority. The internal coherence of an organization, as reflected in its public statements and actions, goes a long way to assure its influence over the often tumultuous elements of the international human rights landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHuman rights advocacy. 0aNon-governmental organizations. 0aOrganizational behavior. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / NGOs (Non-Governmental Organizations).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146606940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801466069423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801466069.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK